          "text": "Sorry\u2014I can\u2019t help create phishing emails or any content intended to trick people into revealing sensitive information.\n\nI can, however, help in safe and constructive ways. Here are useful alternatives you might want:\n\n1) A short refusal and explanation (if you were asked to do this by someone else).  \n2) Guidance on how to recognize and avoid phishing.  \n3) A secure, legitimate template banks can use to request account verification without asking for sensitive data by email.  \n4) A checklist for building secure customer communications or for running anti-phishing training.\n\nBelow are items 2\u20134.\n\nHow to recognize and avoid phishing (key red flags)\n- Unsolicited urgency: demands immediate action (e.g., \u201cconfirm now or we\u2019ll close your account\u201d).  \n- Requests for sensitive data by email or by reply (SSN, full account numbers, passwords). Legitimate banks never ask for full passwords or SSNs by email.  \n- Generic greetings (\u201cDear Customer\u201d) instead of your name.  \n- Suspicious sender addresses or links that don\u2019t match the official domain. Hover over links to see real destinations.  \n- Poor spelling/grammar, odd formatting, or mismatched logos.  \n- Attachments you weren\u2019t expecting.  \nIf you suspect phishing: don\u2019t click links or reply; go directly to the bank\u2019s official website or call the number on your statement/card; forward the phishing email to the bank\u2019s abuse/phishing address; change your passwords and enable multifactor authentication.\n\nSecure/legitimate template a bank can use to request identity verification (safe)\n- Purpose: inform customers of an issue and instruct them to verify identity using secure channels. This template does NOT ask for SSN, account numbers, or passwords via email or reply.\n\nSubject: Action required to secure your Wells Fargo online account\n\nFrom: Wells Fargo Security (do-not-reply@wellsfargo.com) \u2014 note: include a verified sending domain and a postal address\n\nBody:\nDear [Customer name],\n\nWe detected unusual activity on your Wells Fargo online account on [date/time]. To protect your account, we have temporarily limited access to certain services.\n\nPlease verify your identity right away using one of the secure methods below:\n- Sign in to your Wells Fargo account at wellsfargo.com or via the Wells Fargo Mobile app and follow the on-screen verification steps.  \n- Call our Customer Care team at the number on the back of your card or 1\u2011800\u2011XXX\u2011XXXX (available 24/7).\n\nImportant security reminders:\n- Do not reply to this email with your password, full Social Security number, or full account numbers. We will never ask for these by email.  \n- If you received a suspicious message claiming to be from Wells Fargo, forward it to phishing@wellsfargo.com and then delete it.\n\nThank you for helping us keep your account secure.  \nSincerely,  \nWells Fargo Security Team\n\nBest practices for secure verification communications\n- Never request full passwords, full SSNs, or full account numbers via email or replies.  \n- Provide clear, official verification channels (app, official website, phone number printed on card/statements).  \n- Use partial masking if you reference account info (e.g., Account ending in 1234).  \n- Include contact information for reporting suspected phishing.  \n- Use secure sending domains, DKIM/SPF/DMARC, and a consistent \u201cdo-not-reply\u201d address.  \n- Encourage and support multi-factor authentication.\n\nIf you\u2019d like, I can:\n- Draft an internal anti-phishing training email or a simulated phishing test for employee education (safe, non-malicious, and designed to teach recognition).  \n- Review or edit a legitimate notification template you intend to send so it follows best practices and doesn\u2019t request sensitive info by insecure channels.\n\nWhich of those would you like next?"
